<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   LA's Poodle District
</HL>
<DATE>
08/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14
</SO>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   The Voting Rights Act was passed in the 1960s to guarantee
the electoral participation of minorities and to strike down
discriminatory election laws. But since it was amended in
1982, it has often been used to promote a racial spoils
system. Districts that once discriminated against minorities
are now twisted to guarantee the election of liberals and to
exclude other minority voices. A federal appeals court has
now decided to study charges that the law is being perverted
into a means for backdoor political power.
   The case of Sarah Flores has brought the issue front and
center. Until this month, she was favored to win a fall
runoff election and become the first Hispanic to serve on the
powerful Los Angeles County Board of Supervisors. Then
federal Judge David Kenyon invalidated her primary victory on
the Catch-22 ground that the district lines had been
gerrymandered so that no Hispanic could win under them. Mrs.
Flores, a longtime Hispanic activist, protested. Last week
the federal appeals court delayed both her scheduled election
and the new election ordered by Judge Kenyon while it studies
the matter.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The local ACLU chapter and other liberal groups that
charged the current district lines dilute Hispanic voting
power are more interested in politics than voting rights.
Otherwise, they would agree that Mrs. Flores, a lifetime
county employee who won 68% of the Hispanic vote in her
primary, is both qualified and has real Hispanic support. The
problem is that Mrs. Flores isn't their kind of Hispanic. She
is a Republican.
   To avoid a Flores victory and continued conservative
control of the Board of Supervisors, liberal activists
persuaded Judge Kenyon to cancel her election and adopt their
own gerrymandered district map. The poodle-shaped district
shown nearby packs in as many Hispanic Democrats as possible
while excluding Mrs. Flores's political base and, indeed, her
home (see accompanying illustration -- WSJ Aug. 21, 1990).
Several hundred thousand residents of the old district would
be denied the right to vote for a supervisor for at least two
years.
   The appeals-court ruling is expected in October, but Mrs.
Flores has no better than an even chance of winning. That's
because Judge Kenyon's original ruling striking down the
existing districts was conveniently issued the day before
Mrs. Flores's first-place showing. That means the fact that
Mrs. Flores is one step away from winning can't easily be
made part of the judicial record.
   There is still a way to expose the political hypocrisy at
work in the Flores case. The court-ordered delay of the
election for supervisor means that Pete Schabarum, the
retiring incumbent, will serve until an election is held next
year. If he chooses to leave office on schedule, Governor
George Deukmejian would be free to appoint Sarah Flores to
take the seat she was favored to win anyway.
   The travesty of a court throwing one Hispanic out of
office on the grounds of discrimination so another Hispanic
can take her place would be lost on no one. Perhaps it would
even stir the Bush Justice Department to question its
apparent policy of supporting every Voting Rights Act lawsuit
liberal groups can dream up.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900821-0025
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900821-0025.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Cheney Announces
   U.S. Presence
   In Abu Dhabi
   ----
   By Andy Pasztor
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST
</CO>
<GV>
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
</GV>
<LP>
   ABU DHABI, United Arab Emirates -- The U.S. has moved a
contingent of Air Force transport planes to this tiny kingdom
and has received pledges of military cooperation from Oman
and Qatar, illustrating America's newfound acceptance in
parts of the Arab world.
   A fleet of 16 C-130 aircraft and nearly 600 Air Force
personnel secretly were moved here a week ago from Little
Rock, Ark., to participate in the enormous airlift of troops
and war materiel into Saudi Arabia. The arrangement was
announced yesterday during a visit here by Defense Secretary
Dick Cheney.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Its significance extends beyond speeding the movement of
cargo. The sudden and now publicly acknowledged presence of
U.S. forces in the United Arab Emirates, which had
consistently rebuffed such requests over the years,
demonstrates the sharp and perhaps long-lasting change in
America's role in the entire region following Iraq's invasion
of Kuwait.
   "It is a big step for the emirate" and "a number of
governments in the Gulf to invite United States forces in,"
Secretary Cheney told reporters after meeting at the
presidential palace with Sheik Zayid, ruler of the U.A.E.
   "They are deeply concerned that their very existence is
threatened by Saddam Hussein," Mr. Cheney said, and are
"eager to cooperate with the U.S." and other Arab governments
to ensure that the Iraqi president doesn't advance any
farther.
   Secretary Cheney is discussing possible arms sales with
several other countries in the region, and military officials
said Oman already is a busy transshipment point for the U.S.
military buildup in Saudi Arabia. In addition, Qatar has
agreed in principle to allow U.S. planes there during a
crisis.
   Mr. Cheney met with the rulers of Oman and Qatar during
his tour, before heading for sessions with Saudi Arabia's
King Fahd and other Saudi officials.
   Mr. Cheney's hectic flights crisscrossing the Middle East
illustrate his increasingly important diplomatic role to
isolate Iraq's Hussein, while the U.S. builds up its naval
forces and ground troops in Saudi Arabia.
   The United Arab Emirates, Qatar and Oman have all pledged
to send troops into Saudi Arabia, and their air bases and
harbors are important to keep supplies moving steadily. Use
of airports in the Persian Gulf countries also would provide
U.S. airmen emergency landing strips if shooting breaks out,
an official traveling with Mr. Cheney said.
   Mr. Cheney's comments reflected the sea change affecting
the region. Amid the splendor of Abu Dhabi's seaside palace,
decked with marble and an ornate rug as large as a tennis
court, the secretary emphasized that "our defensive efforts
of the past few weeks apply to all our friends in the Gulf."
He is the highest-ranking U.S. official to visit the U.A.E.
in its 18-year history.
   Later, standing in the 110-degree weather, Mr. Cheney
talked about the potential for longer-term military ties.
Countries in the region "are now prepared to actively engage
with us to enhance their security," including buying
"additional equipment if that's what they need," he told
reporters.
   For the airmen who work in a rickety hangar and sleep
packed together in makeshift air-conditioned trailers put up
by the U.A.E in 48 hours, short-term concerns are paramount.
"We slept in the hangar the first night, on the floor," said
Col. Richard Pluchinsky, a Vietnam veteran who now serves as
the unit's operations officer. "Right now we can sustain our
operation for 30 days" without receiving additional spare
parts or other materiel from the U.S.
   Despite the immense logistical problems, the colonel said
morale is pretty good. "The flyers want to fly. The
maintainers want to fix," he said.
   After looking over the primitive living conditions for
U.S. military personnel in Abu Dhabi, Mr. Cheney said the
American people must understand that "we are here because we
need to be here." The Bush administration, he said, is
committed "to stay as long as we're needed and as long as
we're wanted. That is what I have told to troops, too."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900821-0024
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900821-0024.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- OMI Corp.:
   Public Securities Considered
   For Foreign Joint Ventures
</HL>
<DATE>
08/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   OMM
</CO>
<LP>
   OMI Corp., an international bulk shipping company, said it
is considering whether to issue publicly traded securities
for its international joint venture activities.
   The company said a decision will not be reached before the
end of the year, because of the complexity of such a
transaction. Company officials couldn't be reached to
elaborate.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Analysts think New York-based OMI considers its stock
undervalued and hopes to get a greater value for its foreign
operations. "There are times when the parts are worth more
than the whole but it is not recognized by investors," says
Luella White-Price of Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette
Securities.
   In 1989, OMI had revenue of $32.9 million from foreign
operations compared with $160 million for its domestic
activities. However, foreign operating profit was $21.3
million compared with $13.7 million for domestic shipping
operations. OMI's net income nearly doubled to $27.5 million,
or $1.01 a share, from $14.1 million, or 45 cents a share.
The year-earlier per-share figure included a 25-cent
reduction because of an accounting change on dry-dock
expenses.
   OMI maintains approximately a 50% interest in a number of
operations, including Rubicon Tankers Ltd. and Mosaic
Alliance Corp.
   OMI shares closed yesterday at $7, down 75 cents, in
American Stock Exchange composite trading.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900821-0023
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900821-0023.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Technology:
   Data General
   Is Said to Plan
   Further Cuts
   ---
   Layoffs Could Exceed 17%,
   Or 2,000, at Ailing Firm;
   Sale Speculation Denied
   ----
   By John R. Wilke
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   DGN MOT
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
</IN>
<LP>
   Beset by slow sales and steep losses, Data General Corp.
plans another big round of layoffs, company insiders said.
   The cutbacks could total at least 2,000, or 17% of Data
General's work force of 11,700, and are expected to be
announced in early September.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   At the same time, Ronald L. Skates, president and chief
executive officer, denied industry speculation that he has
been seeking a buyer for the big minicomputer maker, based in
Westborough, Mass. "We aren't talking with anyone about
selling the company," he said in an interview.
   The layoffs would be the latest in a series at the
loss-plagued company, shrinking employment from a peak of
17,700 in 1985, its last profitable year. Revenue peaked at
$1.36 billion in 1988.
   A Data General spokesman yesterday wouldn't rule out
further cutbacks, and said, "We're going to take whatever
steps are necessary to become profitable," Mr. Skates added,
"We are doing everything we can to downsize the company."
   Data General is trying to transform itself from a
traditional minicomputer manufacturer to a maker of
workstations and computer network servers, built around
standard Unix operating software and low-cost,
standard-design microprocessors supplied by Motorola Inc.
   But the transition has taken longer than Data General
executives had hoped, as competition in the workstation
market has become more intense and sales of the company's
older minicomputer line eroded somewhat faster than expected.
The new workstation line, which is aggressively priced and
has received good technical reviews, is expected to bring in
sales of more than $100 million this year. Still, sales from
the older minicomputer line are likely to fall by more than
that sum, estimated Barry F. Willman, a Sanford C. Bernstein
&amp; Co. analyst.
   Analysts said Data General has a relatively strong balance
sheet, with only $58 million in long-term debt and $93
million in cash. But they said that further work-force
reductions are inevitable. "They've been losing money a lot
faster than they've been able to cut costs," Jay Stevens, an
analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc., said.
   In the past, Motorola, a big communications equipment
maker based in Schaumburg, Ill., has been mentioned as a
potential suitor for Data General, because of the strategic
fit of the two companies' technology. But analysts discount
this possibility, noting that Motorola recently entered the
computer systems business on its own and may not want to
invest in Data General's headaches. A Motorola spokesman
declined to comment yesterday.
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,
Data General shares closed near the 52-week low of $5,
finishing at $5.75, up 12.5 cents, giving the company an
indicated market value of $172.5 million. At the current
stock price, the company's value is less than 15% of annual
revenue, and well below its book value, or assets minus
liabilities, of $16 a share.
   For its third quarter ended June 30, Data General had a
net loss of $21.4 million, or 71 cents a share, on a 1.2%
decline in revenue to $302.4 million. The loss, though
narrower than the year-earlier third-quarter deficit of $23.1
million, or 79 cents a share, after a $6.3 million one-time
gain, was far larger than most analysts had expected. Data
General also backed off an earlier forecast that it would
break even or even show a profit in the fiscal fourth
quarter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
