900821-0016.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   Crew of a U.S. Warship in the Red Sea
   Stands Ready to Enforce the Blockade
   ----
   By Andy Pasztor
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A16
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST
</CO>
<IN>
PETROLEUM (PET)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
MARINE TRANSPORTATION (MAR)
</IN>
<GV>
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
</GV>
<LP>
   ABOARD THE USS TICONDEROGA -- Tracing Iraqi cargo in the
middle of the Red Sea has so far been more exasperating than
hazardous for the nearly 400 sailors aboard this
guided-missile cruiser.
   Sometimes the biggest problem is finding the right radio
frequency to reach vessels in the busy shipping lanes. When
contact is made, some captains change course to steer away
from the warship but don't indicate their destination.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   At other times, Capt. Morris Foote has to worry about
small coastal freighters that he says stay in Egypt's
territorial waters and may try to work their way into the
Jordanian port of Aqaba, a potentially large hole in the
international interdiction net against Iraq. U.S. ships
closer to Aqaba and other ports have the final responsibility
of determining whether Iraqi cargo is involved, and the U.S.
would intercept ships only in international waters.
   But as tensions heat up in the Middle East, Capt. Foote
and his crew know they will find it even more difficult to
control shipments to Iraq and protect the U.S. fleet in the
Red Sea. "There have been a few cases where we hailed a ship
and got no response," Lt. Cmdr. Steve Miller, the
Ticonderoga's executive officer, said a few days ago. "But
you don't know if it's a {radio} frequency problem or
something much more serious."
   The volatility became clear over the weekend, when
American warships fired warning shots at two Iraqi vessels
believed to be carrying outbound cargoes of oil.
   "When we start getting into the business of firing warning
shots, you're never sure of the reaction," Capt. Foote told
reporters.
   In many ways, life aboard "The Tico" -- as the crew
affectionately calls this 10,000-ton cruiser -- reveals the
risks and difficulties of the Navy's massive show of force.
The Ticonderoga's sophisticated radars, which can
simultaneously track large numbers of ships and planes for
more than 250 miles, also serve as the primary air-defense
warning for the carrier USS Dwight D. Eisenhower and its
support ships.
   "I'm ready at a moment's notice to fire a warning shot if
I have to," Capt. Foote told reporters who visited his ship
last weekend. If a hostile plane heads directly for the
Ticonderoga, he said, "I could have guns shooting in 10
seconds . . . and have missiles shooting in less than that."
   "The crew understand this is serious business, and they
know the president isn't joking," Capt. Foote said. "They all
have cars. They have motorcycles. I don't think any of them
fail to see the importance of fuel."
   All crew members have been issued gas masks and protective
clothing in the event chemical weapons are used by the
Iraqis.
   Inside the hushed, air-conditioned core of the ship --
called the combat information center -- the pale green light
from computer consoles and a giant, computer-generated map of
the region reflects off Capt. Foote's face. He presses a
button, and the image pans out to show the precise speed and
location of distant ships that won't reach the carrier task
force for days. Little half-moons identify the position of 50
or so planes that the ship's computers monitor every hour.
   In the blinding sunlight on deck, a few nervous sailors
with flak jackets, M-14 rifles slung over their shoulders and
.45-caliber pistols on their hips stand ready to make good on
the U.S. blockade. "We just call ourselves the
visit-and-search party," said the 27-year-old lieutenant in
charge. (Defense Department rules allow identifying only
senior officers.)
   If a ship is suspected of carrying Iraqi goods, these
sailors would take a small boat to board it and inspect the
cargo. "Every ship in the fleet has been asked to put
together such teams," said the native of Owings Mills, Md.
Ship captains are required to consult closely with senior
officers before taking such hostile action.
   Most of all, Capt. Foote worries about the long-term
impact on his crew's nerves. "It's very hard to be on
five-minute alert for six months," he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900821-0015
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900821-0015.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Harleysville to Buy
   Property-Casualty
   Lines From USLICO
</HL>
<DATE>
08/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C13
</SO>
<CO>
   HGIC USC
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<LP>
   HARLEYSVILLE, Pa. -- Harleysville Group Inc. and its
parent company, Harleysville Mutual Insurance Co., announced
an agreement to acquire the property and casualty insurance
operations of USLICO Corp., for $135 million in cash and
securities.
   Under the agreement, Harleysville Group and Harleysville
Mutual will purchase all of the capital stock issued and
outstanding of Hawkeye Insurance, based in Des Moines, Iowa,
and its consolidated subsidiaries: United Security Insurance
Co., also based in Des Moines, and Western States Insurance
Co., based in Freeport, Ill.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The transaction price of $135 million will consist of a
cash payment of $110 million, of which $93 million will be
contributed by Harleysville Group, which is a publicly traded
company. Harleysville Mutual will contribute $17 million and
will issue a $25 million, seven-year, 10% note to USLICO.
Immediately prior to the closing of the deal, Hawkeye will
return to USLICO 500,000 common shares of USLICO.
   Bradford W. Mitchell, chairman and chief executive officer
of Harleysville Group, said that the acquisition may have a
moderately dilutive effect on the company's per-share
earnings next year and in 1992, but that it "will have an
anti-dilutive effect on our earnings after that time."
   Mr. Mitchell said the acquisition of USLICO's
property-casualty business will help Harleysville continue
its strategic plan to build its national network of regional
insurance companies. The acquisition will give Harleysville,
which now operates four regional property-casualty insurers
that cover the East Coast, a new presence in Midwest and
Western states. The company will have operations in 34
states, up from 19.
   In a separate but related transaction, Harleysville Mutual
will sell its wholly owned subsidiary, Harleysville Life
Insurance Co., to USLICO for a $17 million, seven-year, 10%
note that Harleysville will hold in its investment portfolio.
</TEXT>
