<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
08/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   BUDGET GAP PROJECTIONS for next year are widening by tens
of billions of dollars because of higher defense spending and
an economic slowdown resulting from the Mideast crisis, U.S.
officials say. A record deficit of $250 billion to $300
billion is likely, which could force severe Gramm-Rudman
spending cuts. Bush, meanwhile, said he will "oppose the
defense budget slashers."
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   OPEC rejected a call by Saudi Arabia and Venezuela for an
emergency meeting, leaving them free to pump more oil on
their own. The group may still meet informally. Crude prices
climbed further yesterday, and gasoline futures surged.
   ---
   Interco agreed tentatively to give bondholders 95% of the
troubled furniture and shoe company's common stock in a debt
swap, plus the right to approve a new slate of directors.
   ---
   Data General plans to lay off at least 2,000, or 17%, of
its employees, company insiders said. Steep losses at the
computer maker are prompting the latest round of cutbacks.
   ---
   First Interstate Bancorp suspended its dividend
reinvestment plan, which was intended to help rebuild the
company's capital base.
   ---
   Boeing received $650 million in firm aircraft orders from
All Nippon Airways. The Japanese carrier also took out new
options to buy $3 billion more of the Seattle firm's jets.
   ---
   RJR Nabisco's recent $2.25 billion loan is getting a cool
reception from the regional and foreign banks asked to take
on some of the debt. The smaller banks want more of the
sizable fees paid to the original lenders.
   ---
   Blue-chip stock prices rose in thin trading, but smaller
issues didn't fare as well. The Dow Jones industrials rose
11.64 points. Bond prices were flat, while the dollar ended
mixed.
   ---
   Some individual investors are optimistic about the outlook
for stocks, showing a confidence not common among the
market's professionals.
   ---
   Northrop's accord in February to plead guilty to faking
test data called for the U.S. to drop its criminal
investigation of at least 11 other areas.
   ---
   Soybean oil futures traders are reporting rumors that one
firm is trying to corner the market, a year after authorities
acted to block a suspected bid to dominate the soybean
market.
   ---
   Volvo unveiled a new top model, as Swedish car makers
prepare for Japanese competition in Europe.
   ---
   The Cirrus and Plus networks of automated tellers agreed
to give each other's customers access to their machines. But
individual banks may opt not to participate in the plan.
   ---
   Denison Mines posted an $84.9 million second-quarter loss,
after the Toronto company wrote down half of its oil and gas
assets and provided for the cost of reducing its work force.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 129,630,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2656.44, up 11.64; transportation 930.29, up 6.38; utilities
201.46, up 0.32.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3337.25, up
0.82.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 134.23, off 0.22;
spot index 133.48, off 0.35.
   Dollar: 146.44 yen, off 1.14; 1.5650 marks, up 0.0155.
</TEXT>
