<HL>
   Union Members Urge
   Triton Shareholders
   To Reject Merger Plan
</HL>
<DATE>
08/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   TGL IMI LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   SAN DIEGO -- A small group of union employees involved in
labor contract negotiations with one of the subsidiaries of
Triton Group Ltd. are urging Triton shareholders to reject a
proposed merger with Intermark Inc.
   The merger is unfair to Triton shareholders and would hurt
union members by weakening Triton and its subsidiaries, said
Richard Zell, secretary-treasurer of United Food &amp; Commercial
Workers Local 1119 in the San Francisco area.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Under the merger agreement, Triton holders would receive
1.4 shares of Intermark common stock for each share of Triton
common. Intermark, a San Diego-based holding company that
already owns a 51.6% stake in Triton, would be the surviving
entity.
   Roughly 300 United Food union members are employed by
Liquor Barn, a retail chain with 65 stores in California.
Only 11 are members of Local 1119, Mr. Zell said. Triton,
also based in San Diego, acquired a two-thirds interest in
Liquor Barn in October.
   In recent weeks, contract talks between Liquor Barn and
its food union employees have stalled. Mr. Zell said that
Liquor Barn management has proposed "a long list of
takeaways" and "is trying to deprive members of union
representation." The workers' contract expired last month.
   Mitchell Woodbury, vice president and corporate counsel
for Triton and Intermark, said that Triton "has been
bargaining in good faith." The merger proposal is "fair, just
and equitable" to shareholders of both companies, he said.
   Mr. Woodbury said Triton has rejected requests by the
union for the company's shareholder lists "as not being made
in compliance with applicable law." Local 1119 purchased
advertising space in this newspaper to urge shareholders to
vote against the merger. Shareholders will vote on the
proposal at Triton's annual meeting Aug. 30.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900821-0001
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900821-0001.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   United Telecom Acts
   To Revamp Sprint's
   Sales and Service Line
</HL>
<DATE>
08/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C13
</SO>
<CO>
   UT GTE
</CO>
<IN>
DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)
TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (TLS)
</IN>
<LP>
   WESTWOOD, Kan. -- United Telecommunications Inc. moved to
reorganize the sales and service operation of its troubled
long-distance telephone unit, US Sprint Communications Co.
   The revamping, which United Telecom said will cut 500
administrative jobs while adding "hundreds" of sales
positions, comes on the heels of a dismal second-quarter
showing by Sprint, the nation's third-largest long-distance
provider.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Sprint posted a $42 million operating loss for the period,
leading to a 55% profit drop for United Telecom and providing
a nasty shock for Wall Street analysts, who had expected a
much smaller decline. United Telecom stock plunged 23% on the
news to $29.50 a share and recently bottomed out in the $23
to $25 range.
   As part of a previously announced plan to cut 1,000 jobs,
Sprint said it will refocus its National Markets operation,
cutting three of its five marketing and service groups. The
customers served by the three discontinued groups, which
handled accounts generating monthly billings between $2,000
and $10,000, will be split between the two remaining groups.
Those two groups, based in Atlanta and Kansas City, Mo.,
previously handled Fortune 1000 accounts and residential
customers.
   Separately, William Esrey, United Telecom's chairman and
chief executive officer, said in an interview that despite
the recent decline in share price, the company isn't
considering buying back any of its stock.
   Without naming any specific targets, Mr. Esrey said United
Telecom wants to retain its ability to use the stock in place
of cash in making acquisitions.
   A company spokesman said no one, either from within the
company or from the investment community, has been lobbying
for a buy-back.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
